Scenario 1: Production Server Not Reachable


Q: Server is DOWN. What are your steps?
1. Check monitoring alerts (Nagios/Zabbix).
2. Ping server → check network reachability.
 #sudo ping -c 5 Server Name / IP Address
3. Try SSH → verify access.
 #ssh username@servername/IP address
4. Check hypervisor/cloud console.
5. Verify CPU, memory, disk, network.
$CPU #top , #htop,#uptime, #lscpu, #cat /proc/cpuinfo, #ps aux --sort=-%cpu | head

$MEMORY#top ,#htop, #free -m, #swapon -s , #cat /proc/meminfo #vmstat #ps aux --sort=-%mem | head 

$DISK #df -h, #du -sh /filesystemname, #iostat -xz 1 3 #lsblk 

$Network #ip addr, #iftop, #route -rn #ss -tulnp #ping google.com #nslookup google.com

6. Check last changes (patch, reboot).
#last reboot, #uptime, #who -b #last -x | grep reboot
#yum history # yum history info, #dnf history, #dnf history info,# lastlog #last,#history , # grep -i reboot /var/log/messages ,# journalctl -b -1

7. Restore services and inform stakeholders.
#systemctl --failed #systemctl status <service-name> #systemctl start <service-name> #systemctl restart <service-name> #systemctl enable <service-name> 
8. Perform RCA and preventive actions.

Scenario 2: High Load but Low CPU Usage
Q: Load average is high but CPU is low. Why?
Because load includes processes waiting for I/O. I check disk latency and memory using:
#iostat -x
#vmstat
#free -h
#mount | grep nfs
#nfsstat
#ps -eo state,pid,cmd | grep "^D"
# ps aux | grep Z
# Root cause could be disk I/O wait or swap usage.

Scenario 3: Disk Full in Production
Q: Root filesystem is 100%. How do you fix without downtime?
Identify large files using #du, 
Clear rotated logs.
Compress old files
#df -h / #df -i / #du -xh / --max-depth=1 | sort -hr 
#du -sh /var/log/* # truncate -s 0 /var/log/messages
#truncate -s 0 /var/log/secure
#> /var/log/messages #journalctl --disk-usage
#journalctl --vacuum-time=7d #yum clean all
#rm -rf /tmp/* #rm -rf /var/tmp/* #lsof +L1
Extend LVM online if needed.
#lvextend -L +10G /dev/mapper/rhel-root
#xfs_growfs /
#resize2fs /dev/mapper/rhel-root
